Nearby_cREs.summary: This table displays all cREs within 1M basepairs of the selected cRE, with actual distances displayed in basepairs. Clicking a cRE link performs a search for that cRE in SCREEN.
Nearby_cREs.title: Nearby cREs Table

cREsWithinTAD.summary: This table displays all other cREs within the selected cRE’s TAD. Links perform a search for the given cRE.
cREsWithinTAD.title: Other cREs within TAD Table

CellTypeAgnosticClassification.summary:
Red, yellow, and blue squares indicate promoter-like, enhancer-like, and CTCF-only cREs, classified in a cell-type-agonistic manner, as explained in the About page.


Promoter-like cREs (red) have maximal H3K4me3 Z-scores across all cell types greater than 1.64 (i.e., 95th percentile) . Moreover, they are within 2kb of a GENCODE TSS or have maximal H3K27ac Z-scores less than 1.64.


Enhancer-like cREs (yellow) have maximal H3K27ac Z-scores across all cell types greater than 1.64. Moreover, they are more than 2kb away from a GENCODE TSS or have maximal H3K4me3 Z-scores less than 1.64.


cREs that are not classified as promoter-like or enhancer-like but have maximal CTCF Z-scores across all cell types greater than 1.64 are classified as CTCF-only (blue).
CellTypeAgnosticClassification.title: Cell type agnostic classifications of cREs

DifferentialGeneMouse.summary:
This column lists the three nearest genes to each cRE by linear genomic distance. Two sets of genes are provided, one set from protein coding (pc) genes, and one set from all annotated genes.


Clicking the gene link will lead to a page that displays a bar plot of the expression levels of the gene across all available cell types.


Clicking the delta sign to the right of each gene (Δ) will lead to a page which displays the differential expression of the gene (if data is available) between two user-specified cell types or samples, the differential expression of its neighbor genes, and the differential H3K27ac Z scores of the cREs in the genomic loci.
DifferentialGeneMouse.title: Nearest genes

CTCFZ-scores.summary: This table displays the CTCF Z-scores for this cRE across all cell types with CTCF ChIP-seq data available. The right hand column displays the Z-score for the cRE based only on CTCF ChIP-seq data. Where DNase and CTCF ChIP-seq data are both available for a given cell type, the middle column displays the average of the cRE’s DNase Z-score and CTCF Z-score in the given cell type. The table is sortable by clicking the column headers.
CTCFZ-scores.title: CTCF Z-scores

DE_cRE_Table.summary: This table displays all cREs within the plot window. It lists the cRE’s accession, start coordinate, and length, as well as the difference in Z-scores between the two selected cell types (H3K4me3 Z-scores for a promoter-like cRE and H3K27ac Z-scores for an enhancer-like cRE). A positive value indicates a higher Z-score in Cell Type 1 and a negative value indicates a higher Z-score in Cell Type 2. Clicking a cRE’s accession performs a search for that cRE.
DE_cRE_Table.title: Differentially-Expressed cRE Table

CellTypeTableAccessionCol.summary:
A star indicates that there is at least one cell type in which this cRE has a DNase Z-score higher than 1.64 and at least one of the three Z-scores (H3K4me3, H3K27ac, or CTCF) higher than 1.64.


P indicates that the cRE is proximal (within 2kb judged by the nearest edge) to a GENCODE-annotated transcription start site (TSS). D indicates that the cRE is distal to all GENCODE TSSs.


Red, yellow, and blue squares indicate that the H3K4me3, H3K27ac, and CTCF Z-scores, respectively, for the cRE exceed the cutoff of 1.64 (i.e., 95th percentile) in at least one cell type. As explained in the About page, all cREs must have DNase Z-score greater than 1.64 (i.e., the 95th percentile) in at least one cell type, hence they would have all been assigned a green square, which is omitted for clarity.
CellTypeTableAccessionCol.title: Cell type agnostic classifications of cREs

CellTypeFacet.summary:
The cell type facet allows you to filter the cREs in your search results based on their biochemical activities in a particular cell type, measured as DNase, H3K4me3, H3K27ac, or CTCF Z-scores in that cell type. Click a cell type to select it, and additional Z-score columns will appear in the cRE Search Results table for the DNase-seq or ChIP-seq data available in that cell type. You can search for a cell type using the search box above the table, but you still need to click the cell type to select it once you have found it. When a cell type is selected, simply click its name again to deselect it.


For each cell type, the 2X2 colorful square on the right indicates which datasets are available in this cell type—green for DNase-seq, red for H3K4me3 ChIP-seq, yellow for H3K27ac ChIP-seq, and blue for CTCF ChIP-seq.


Once a cell type is selected, you can use the Z-score facet below to filter search results based on biochemical activity in the selected cell type. By default, selecting a cell type filters the search results to only include elements with a DNase-seq Z-score of at least 1.64 (corresponding to the 95th percentile for a one-tailed test)  in the selected cell type, if DNase-seq data is available for the selected cell type.
CellTypeFacet.title: Cell Type Facet

RAMPAGEOverview.summary: RAMPAGE (RNA Annotation and Mapping of Promoters for Analysis of Gene Expression) data allows for the annotation of and expression at transcription start sites with nucleotide precision. Here, we display the sum of signal (from ENCODE Data Coordination Center's RAMPAGE pipeline) in a ±50bp window around GENCODE V19 annotated TSSs for the cRE's nearest protein coding gene. As, this signal is strand specific, we display signal from both the + and - strands for each experiment.
RAMPAGEOverview.title: RAMPAGE Signal of Nearby TSSs

CoordinateFacet.summary: The coordinate facet allows you to filter your search results based on genomic coordinate. To adjust the selected coordinates, you may either drag the sliders or type values into the textboxes. Above the slider, the histogram displays the distribution of cREs across the selected chromosome.
CoordinateFacet.title: Coordinate Facet

Nearby_genes.summary: This table displays the nearest genes by linear distance to the selected cRE, with actual distances displayed in basepairs. Gene links lead to the GeneCards page for the given gene.
Nearby_genes.title: Nearby Genes Table

GWAS_Studies_Facet.summary:
The Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) facet lists the GWAS studies that have been loaded into SCREEN for analysis. The first step is to select a GWAS study from the list by clicking its row in the table. A selected study may be deselected by clicking its link in the studies facet a second time.


Once a GWAS study is selected, A table is displayed on the right summarizing the statistics of the study, including the total number of linkage disequilibrium (LD) blocks formed by the associated SNPs in the study, how many of these LD blocks overlap a cRE, and the total number of overlapping cREs.  Furthermore, a cell type facet will appear below to allow the display of the biochemical activities of the overlapping cREs in a specific cell type.
GWAS_Studies_Facet.title: Studies Facet

CellTypeSpecifiedClassification.summary: Green, red, yellow, and blue squares indicate that the DNase, H3K4me3, H3K27ac, and CTCF Z-scores respectively for the cRE exceed the cutoff of 1.64 (i.e., 95th percentile) in the selected cell type. Alternatively, a white square indicates the corresponding Z-score is less than 1.64 and a grey square indicates that the corresponding data are missing in the selected cell type.
CellTypeSpecifiedClassification.title: classification of cREs for the selected cell type

Nearby_SNPs.summary: This table displays all single nucleotide polymorphism (SNPs) within 1k basepairs of the selected cRE, with actual distances displayed. Clicking a SNP link leads to the information page for that SNP at ENSEMBL. The UCSC button may be used to visualize the region surrounding the SNP in the UCSC Genome Browser.
Nearby_SNPs.title: Nearby SNPs Table

Z-scoreFacet.summary:
The Z-score facet allows you to filter your search results based on their DNase, H3K4me3, H3K27ac, and CTCF Z-scores. When no cell type is selected, the sliders filter cREs based on maximal Z-scores in each data type across all cell types. When a cell type is selected, their Z-scores in the selected cell type are used for filtering. A minimum Z-score of 1.64 (95th percentile) is recommended for filtering cREs based on activity in a given category.


In some cases, a selected cell type may not have all four types of data available. In this case, the sliders for the missing data types will not display, and a message will appear above the cRE Search Results table explaining that some datasets are missing for the selected cell type.
Z-scoreFacet.title: Z-score Facet

GWAS_Results_Table.summary: This table displays any cREs which overlap SNPs from the selected GWAS study and are predicted to be active in the selected cell type. Each row provides the cRE’s accession, the SNPs from the study that it overlaps, and the nearest protein coding gene by linear distance. The search box at the top right of the table may be used to filter the results by SNP, gene, or cRE accession. The results from the table may be downloaded using the CSV link at the top of the table.
GWAS_Results_Table.title: GWAS Results Table

DNaseZ-scores.summary: This table displays the DNase Z-scores for this cRE across all cell types with DNase-seq data available. The table is sortable by clicking the column headers.
DNaseZ-scores.title: DNase Z-scores

GeneExpression.summary:
This bar plot displays the expression level of a given gene across available cell types and tissues derived from RNA-seq data.


By default, the data displayed is log2(TPM + 0.01), but this may be customized by selecting from the data dropdown; FPKM values are also available and the log scale may be turned off. TPM and RPKM are two metrics of gene expression level and they differ slightly in their approaches to normalizing for sequencing depth and gene length.


The sort order dropdown allows sorting of the data by TPM or FPKM and also allows grouping of the expression values by tissue.


Rolling cursor over the bars displays more information about the experiments that produced the data points, and clicking on a bar redirects to the corresponding experiment at the ENCODE portal.
GeneExpression.title: Gene Expression

CellTypeTree.summary: This tree displays a hierarchical clustering of cell types according to the ranks of the search results. For each pair of cell types, the Spearman correlation of the search results’ ranks for a given assay or assay combination (DNase, H3K4me3, etc.) are computed, and the cell types are then hierarchically clustered according to their correlations with one another. Cell types are color-coded according to tissue. Adjusting the facets at left will cause the tree to refresh. The drop down at the top allows the user to choose which ranks are used to cluster the cell types.
CellTypeTree.title: Cell type hierarchical clustering

H3K27acZ-scores.summary: This table displays the H3K27ac Z-scores for this cRE across all cell types with H3K27ac ChIP-seq data available. The right hand column displays the Z-score for the cRE based only on H3K27ac ChIP-seq data. Where DNase and H3K27ac ChIP-seq data are both available for a given cell type, the middle column displays the average of the cRE’s DNase Z-score and H3K27ac Z-score in the given cell type. The table is sortable by clicking the column headers.
H3K27acZ-scores.title: H3K27ac Z-scores

GWAS_Cell_Types_Facet.summary:
The cell types facet allows you to search for cREs which overlap SNPs from the selected GWAS study by their biochemical activities in a selected cell type. By default, the cell types are sorted by p-value and false discovery rate (FDR), which quantify how significant the GWAS SNPs were enriched in the cRE specific to each cell type, with most significant cell types appearing at the top. Please see the About page of SCREEN for more details on the method for computing significance.


To select a cell type, click its row within the table. Another table will appear to the right, which lists cREs which are predicted to be active in the selected cell type and overlap SNPs from the selected study. Only one cell type may be selected each time; to select a different cell type, simply click its row within the table.
GWAS_Cell_Types_Facet.title: Cell Types Facet

DE_Gene_Table.summary: This table displays all genes within the plot window. It lists the gene name, start coordinate, and strand, as well as the fold change in gene expression between the two selected cell types as computed by DESeq. A positive fold change value indicates the gene is more highly expressed in Cell Type 1, and a negative fold change value indicates the gene is more highly expressed in Cell Type 2.
DE_Gene_Table.title: Differentially-Expressed Genes Table

Intersecting_transcription_factors.summary: This table displays a list of all transcription factors (TFs) with ChIP-seq peaks which intersect the selected cRE. The peaks include all available cell types. The right hand column displays the number of ChIP-seq experiments for the given transcription factor with peaks intersecting the selected cRE. Clicking a table row will display another table below, which lists the cell types in which the TF ChIP-seq experiments were performed, with links to the experiment data at the ENCODE portal.
Intersecting_transcription_factors.title: Transcription Factor Table

IntersectingHistoneMarks.summary: This table displays a list of all histone marks with ChIP-seq peaks which intersect the selected cRE. The peaks include all available cell types. The right hand column displays the number of ChIP-seq experiments for the given histone mark with peaks intersecting the selected cRE. Clicking a table row will display another table below, which lists the cell types in which the histone mark ChIP-seq experiments were performed, with links to the experiment data at the ENCODE portal.
IntersectingHistoneMarks.title: Histone Marks Table

ActivityHeatmap.summary:
The activity heatmap displays the fraction of the search results which are active in each cell type by DNase, promoter, enhancer, and CTCF rank.


An active element is defined as any element with a rank below the predefined threshold of 20,000.
ActivityHeatmap.title: Activity heatmap

GenesWithinTAD.summary: This table displays the genes within this cRE’s TAD. Clicking a gene link leads to the information page for the gene at GeneCards.
GenesWithinTAD.title: Genes within TAD Table

H3K4me3Z-scores.summary: This table displays the H3K4me3 Z-scores for this cRE across all cell types with H3K4me3 ChIP-seq data available. The right hand column displays the Z-score for the cRE based only on H3K4me3 ChIP-seq data. Where DNase and H3K4me3 ChIP-seq data are both available for a given cell type, the middle column displays the average of the cRE’s DNase Z-score and H3K4me3 Z-score. The table is sortable by clicking the column headers.
H3K4me3Z-scores.title: H3K4me3 Z-scores
